<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910906-0004</DOCNO><DOCID>910906-0004.</DOCID><HL>   Car Sales Jump in Italy   For July and August,   Surprise in Slow Year</HL><DATE>09/06/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   F F.RNA FIA G.VOW</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)</MS><IN>AUTOMOBILES (AUT)</IN><RE>EUROPE (EU)FRANCE (FR)GERMANY (GE)ITALY (ITA)MICHIGAN (MI)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)WESTERN EUROPE (WEU)</RE><LP>   MILAN -- Car sales in Italy rose 5.64% in July and jumped7.15% in August from a year earlier in a surprise departurefrom sluggish car sales since last year, the nationalassociation of car manufacturers, Anfia, said.   However, Anfia said the improvement in car sales duringthe two summer months didn't necessarily mark a turnaround ofthe downward trend on the car market.</LP><TEXT>   &quot;It appears the losses posted during the first half of theyear are gradually being reabsorbed,&quot; Anfia said, but added,&quot;in the second half of 1991, although it started out well, itcan't yet be said that the market has definitively changedits direction.&quot;   Anfia predicted that by the end of the year, car salescould reach 2.3 million.   In the first eight months of 1991, car sales fell 1.12%from a year earlier.   Anfia said a total of 213,356 cars were sold in July, upfrom 201,961 in July 1990, while a total of 95,848 cars weresold in August, up from 89,454 a year earlier. Car salestotaled 1,636,338 in the first eight months, down from1,654,864 a year earlier.   Domestic manufacturers, led by Fiat S.p.A., which producesFiat, Lancia, Alfa Romeo brands, controlled 38.29% of thedomestic car market in August, down from 45.45% in July and46.69% last year. Fiat's market share in the first eightmonths slipped to 45.76% from 53.80% in the first eightmonths of last year.   Among foreign producers, Volkswagen AG led with a marketshare of 12.23% in August, up from 8.94% a year before. FordMotor Co. followed closely with a market share of 11.17%,which was up from 7.52% in August of 1990. Renault of Francewas third with a share of 8.90%, up from 7.21%.</TEXT></DOC>